      kicker: "Core Craft",
      dek: `Campaigns are won before they launch. The weeks of planning — building your audience, preparing materials, lining up early backers, and mapping the timeline — decide the outcome far more than anything you do once the clock is running.`,
      seoTitle: "Planning Your Campaign: Pre-Launch Crowdfunding Planning | Filmmaker Genius",
      seoDesc: "Planning a crowdfunding campaign — the pre-launch work (timeline, audience-building, materials, team) that decides whether a film crowdfunding campaign succeeds before it even starts. Chapter 5 of Crowdfunding Your Film.",
      body: `<p>Here's the single most important truth about crowdfunding, and the one most beginners ignore: <strong>campaigns are won or lost in the planning, before the launch button is ever pressed.</strong> The filmmakers who succeed don't launch and hope; they spend weeks — often a month or two — preparing: building and warming up their audience, preparing all their materials (pitch video, page, rewards), lining up early backers who'll pledge in the first 48 hours, and mapping out the campaign's timeline and promotion. By the time they launch, success is already likely, because the foundation is laid. The filmmakers who fail usually launched on impulse with no audience warmed up, no early backers ready, and materials thrown together — and watched the campaign stall in silence. This chapter, opening Module 2, is about the pre-launch planning that determines your fate, because the work you do before the clock starts matters more than anything you do while it's running.</p>

<h2>The pre-launch planning that decides your campaign</h2>

<p>What to do before you launch:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Build and warm up your audience.</b> Grow and engage your email list and social following <em>before</em> launch, so there's a crowd ready to back you on day one.</li>
  <li><b>Line up early backers.</b> Privately secure commitments from friends, family, and close supporters to pledge in the first 24–48 hours — early momentum is critical (next point).</li>
  <li><b>Prepare all materials in advance.</b> Have your pitch video, campaign page, rewards, and images finished before launch — there's no time to make them once you're live.</li>
  <li><b>Map the timeline.</b> Plan the campaign's arc — launch push, mid-campaign updates, final surge — and a promotion calendar for each phase.</li>
  <li><b>Build your team/help.</b> Line up collaborators, ambassadors, or a small team to help share and sustain the campaign — you can't do it all alone for 30 days.</li>
  <li><b>Set the goal and rewards.</b> Finalize a realistic goal and reward tiers (covered in their own chapters) as part of the plan, not on the fly.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Why early momentum makes planning essential</h2>

<p>The reason planning matters so much comes down to a well-known dynamic of crowdfunding: <strong>early momentum drives everything, and you can only manufacture early momentum through preparation.</strong> Campaigns that raise a significant chunk of their goal in the first 48 hours are far more likely to succeed, because early success creates social proof (people back projects that look like they're winning), triggers the platform's algorithms and "popular" placements, and gives you momentum to build on. But that early surge doesn't happen by accident — it happens because you spent the pre-launch weeks warming up an audience and privately lining up backers who pledge the moment you go live. A campaign that launches cold, with no warmed-up audience and no early backers ready, opens to silence, and silence is very hard to recover from: with no early momentum, there's no social proof, no algorithmic boost, and the campaign stalls. This is why the planning phase — building the audience, securing early commitments, preparing everything so launch day is a coordinated push rather than a scramble — is where the campaign is actually won. The launch is just the moment your preparation pays off (or doesn't). A few honest points. First, <em>the first 48 hours are decisive, so engineer them</em> — because early momentum is so predictive, the smartest pre-launch work is lining up enough early backers to make a strong opening, which turns launch day from a gamble into a planned surge. Second, <em>you can't build an audience after you launch</em> — audience-building takes time, so it must happen <em>before</em> the campaign, not during it; launching first and hoping to find backers is backwards. Third, <em>prepare everything in advance</em> — once the clock is running you'll be consumed with promotion and management, with no time to make a video or write reward tiers, so everything must be ready at launch (which is why the video, rewards, and page have their own chapters). Fourth, <em>plan the whole arc, not just the launch</em> — campaigns sag in the middle, so a plan that maps promotion across the launch, the middle, and the final surge sustains momentum through the inevitable lull (the running chapter develops this). Planning your campaign — audience, early backers, materials, timeline, team — is the unglamorous work that decides everything, because a campaign is won before it launches. Do this work, and launch day becomes the start of a likely success rather than a hopeful gamble. With the plan in place, the next chapters build its key pieces — starting with the most consequential number in the whole campaign: your goal. Next, setting your goal and budget.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Campaigns are won before they launch. Early momentum in the first 48 hours drives everything — social proof, algorithms, confidence — and you can only manufacture it by warming up an audience and lining up backers before you go live.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My first campaign, I launched the day I finished the page — no audience warmed up, no backers lined up, just hope. It opened to crickets. A few friends trickled in, but with no early momentum the campaign never caught, and it failed. My second campaign, I spent two months first: growing my email list, personally messaging dozens of people to line up first-day pledges, finishing every material in advance. When I launched, I hit 40% of goal in the first two days because it was all pre-arranged — and that early surge pulled in strangers who saw a winning project. Same film, same me. The difference was entirely the planning I'd done before the launch button.</p>
</div>`,
