      dek: `The pitch video is the heart of your campaign — the single thing most likely to turn a visitor into a backer. Paired with a clear, compelling campaign page, it's your whole pitch. As a filmmaker, this is the part you're built to nail.`,
      seoTitle: "Your Pitch Video & Page: Crowdfunding Pitch Video | Filmmaker Genius",
      seoDesc: "The crowdfunding pitch video and campaign page — how to make a pitch video and page that convert visitors into backers, what to include, and the mistakes that lose pledges. Chapter 8 of Crowdfunding Your Film.",
      body: `<p>If there's one element that most determines whether a campaign converts visitors into backers, it's the <strong>pitch video</strong> — and as a filmmaker, this is the part of crowdfunding you're uniquely equipped to excel at. When someone lands on your campaign page, the video is usually the first thing they engage with, and it does the heavy lifting: it introduces you, conveys what your film is and why it matters, shows that you're capable of making it, and — most importantly — makes an emotional connection that moves someone from "interesting" to "I want to back this." Paired with a clear, well-organized campaign page that answers the practical questions, the video is your entire pitch. The good news for filmmakers is that a compelling pitch video plays directly to your skills; the caution is that the pitch video is <em>not</em> a trailer for your film — it's a personal, direct appeal that follows its own rules. This chapter is about making a pitch video and page that convert. <em>(Note: the pitch video sells the campaign, and it's different from the film itself — some of the strongest pitch videos are simply you talking to camera with heart.)</em></p>

<h2>What makes a pitch video and page work</h2>

<p>The elements that convert visitors to backers:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Lead with the hook and heart.</b> Open with what makes your film compelling and why you care — grab attention and emotion in the first moments.</li>
  <li><b>Show it's you, and you're real.</b> Backers fund people as much as projects — let them see and trust the filmmaker behind the film. Authenticity beats polish.</li>
  <li><b>Say what the money does.</b> Be concrete about what you're raising for and what backers' contributions will make possible — clarity builds confidence.</li>
  <li><b>Make a direct ask.</b> Explicitly ask people to back the film and share it — the video should end on a clear call to action.</li>
  <li><b>Keep it tight.</b> A pitch video should be short (a few minutes) — attention is scarce, so make every second count.</li>
  <li><b>Back it with a clear page.</b> The page should answer the practical questions — the story, the team, the budget, the rewards, the timeline — in a scannable, compelling layout.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Making a pitch that converts</h2>

<p>The way to make a pitch video that works is to remember that <strong>you're not selling a film to a distributor; you're inviting real people to become part of something, and that invitation is personal, emotional, and direct.</strong> The strongest film pitch videos aren't slick trailers — they're the filmmaker, on camera, speaking with genuine passion about why this film needs to exist and why they need help to make it. That authenticity is what converts, because backers fund <em>people</em> and <em>causes</em> as much as projects; they want to believe in you and feel the heart behind the film. So lead with the hook and the emotion, let your real self come through (polish matters far less than sincerity), be concrete about what the money will do (people give more confidently when they know what their contribution enables), and end with a direct, unembarrassed ask to back and share. Then let the campaign page carry the practical load: the page is where a persuaded viewer goes to confirm the details — the story, who you are, the budget, the rewards, the timeline — so it should answer every reasonable question clearly and be easy to scan, with strong images and a compelling written pitch reinforcing the video. Video plus page together are your whole campaign pitch: the video moves people emotionally, the page reassures them practically, and together they turn a visitor into a backer. A few honest points. First, <em>the pitch video isn't a trailer</em> — it's a personal appeal, so resist the urge to just cut a slick teaser; the videos that raise money are the ones where the filmmaker connects directly and asks sincerely. Second, <em>backers fund you, not just the film</em> — your authenticity and passion on camera are what build the trust that opens wallets, so let yourself be real and present rather than hiding behind production value. Third, <em>be concrete about the money</em> — vague "help me make my film" converts worse than "your pledge funds our three shooting days and pays our crew," because specificity builds confidence and shows you've planned. Fourth, <em>the page must answer the questions</em> — a persuaded viewer will scroll to check the details, so a clear, complete, scannable page (story, team, budget, rewards, timeline) closes the pledge that the video opened. Your pitch video and page are the pieces where your filmmaking skill and your sincerity turn interest into pledges — and they're the part of crowdfunding you're most built to nail. With everything prepared — plan, goal, rewards, video, page — Module 3 turns to execution: running the campaign. Next, running the campaign.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The pitch video isn't a trailer — it's you, on camera, inviting real people to be part of something you care about. Backers fund people and causes as much as projects, so lead with heart, be concrete about the money, and ask directly.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>For my first campaign video I made a slick two-minute teaser — moody shots, no me, very "cinematic." It converted terribly. A crowdfunding veteran watched it and said, "Where are <em>you</em>? People aren't backing a trailer; they're backing you." My second video was almost the opposite: me, talking to camera, telling people honestly why this film mattered to me, what their money would do, and asking them plainly to help. It felt vulnerable and unpolished. It raised far more, because it was real. I learned that a pitch video's job isn't to impress — it's to connect, and to ask. The filmmaking skill matters, but the sincerity matters more.</p>
</div>`,
