      dek: `Launch is just the start of a month of daily work. A campaign has a shape — a strong open, a dangerous middle, and a decisive final push — and running it well means managing that whole arc, not just going live and hoping.`,
      seoTitle: "Running the Campaign: Managing a Crowdfunding Campaign Day by Day | Filmmaker Genius",
      seoDesc: "Running a film crowdfunding campaign — managing the launch, the mid-campaign lull, updates, and the final push, day by day, to carry momentum across the finish line. Chapter 9 of Crowdfunding Your Film.",
      body: `<p>You've planned, prepared, and launched — and now comes the part many filmmakers underestimate: <strong>running the campaign for its full duration is a month of daily work, and a campaign has a predictable shape you have to actively manage.</strong> Nearly every campaign follows the same arc: a strong <em>open</em> (your warmed-up audience and lined-up backers create an early surge), a slow, dangerous <em>middle</em> (the initial excitement fades and pledges slow to a trickle — this is where campaigns die), and a decisive <em>final push</em> (the approaching deadline drives a second surge as urgency kicks in). Running the campaign well means managing this whole arc: sustaining the open, fighting through the middle with fresh content and outreach, and mobilizing hard for the final push. Filmmakers who "launch and hope" watch the middle kill their campaign; filmmakers who actively run it carry momentum across the line. This chapter, opening Module 3, is about managing the campaign day by day.</p>

<h2>Managing the campaign arc</h2>

<p>How to run each phase:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Launch strong.</b> Fire your lined-up backers and audience on day one for a big early surge — the momentum and social proof that pull in more (from the planning chapter).</li>
  <li><b>Thank and engage backers.</b> Personally thank backers, respond to comments and messages, and make people feel appreciated — engaged backers share and bring others.</li>
  <li><b>Fight the middle with fresh content.</b> The mid-campaign lull is normal and deadly — post updates, share new material, spotlight rewards, and keep giving people reasons to look again.</li>
  <li><b>Post updates.</b> Regular campaign updates (milestones, behind-the-scenes, new rewards, stretch goals) keep momentum and remind people to share.</li>
  <li><b>Mobilize for the final push.</b> As the deadline nears, urgency returns — rally hard, remind everyone the clock is running, and drive the closing surge.</li>
  <li><b>Watch the numbers &amp; adapt.</b> Track your pace against your goal and timeline, and adjust your effort — push harder if you're behind, celebrate milestones if ahead.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Carrying momentum through the middle</h2>

<p>The heart of running a campaign well is <strong>surviving the middle — because the open and the close mostly take care of themselves (early backers surge in, deadline urgency surges at the end), but the long middle is where campaigns quietly die, and only active management gets you through it.</strong> After the launch excitement fades, pledges slow dramatically; your core supporters have given, the novelty is gone, and the deadline is still far off. This is the danger zone, and the campaigns that fail usually fail here — the filmmaker, exhausted from launch, goes quiet, the campaign stalls, and momentum never returns. The way through is relentless, varied engagement: keep posting updates (a milestone hit, a behind-the-scenes clip, a new reward, a stretch goal), keep reaching new pockets of potential backers (the marketing chapter goes deeper), keep thanking and engaging the backers you have so they keep sharing, and keep giving people fresh reasons to look at your page again. You're manufacturing the momentum the middle won't provide on its own. Then, as the deadline approaches, urgency naturally returns — people who meant to back "later" realize later is now — so you mobilize hard for the final push, reminding everyone the clock is running and rallying a closing surge that often rivals the launch. Running the campaign is a month-long job of sustaining an open, grinding through a middle, and finishing strong. A few honest points. First, <em>the middle is where campaigns die, so plan your energy for it</em> — many filmmakers spend everything on launch and have nothing left for the long middle, so pace yourself and save fuel (updates, content, outreach) for the dangerous stretch. Second, <em>updates are momentum</em> — regular, varied campaign updates are one of your best tools for keeping the campaign alive through the middle and reminding people to share, so plan a cadence of them in advance. Third, <em>engaged backers are your amplifiers</em> — thanking and involving your backers turns them into advocates who bring others, so treating existing backers well is also a growth strategy. Fourth, <em>the final 48 hours can rival the launch</em> — deadline urgency drives a real closing surge, so save a coordinated final push (and let waverers know it's now or never) to capitalize on it. Running the campaign is the demanding daily work that turns a good plan into a funded film: launch strong, engage constantly, fight through the middle, and finish hard. With the campaign running, the next chapter deepens one crucial part of that work — reaching backers beyond your own circle. Next, marketing and reaching backers.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The open and the close take care of themselves; the middle is where campaigns die. Surviving it takes relentless, varied engagement — updates, outreach, thanking backers — to manufacture the momentum the middle won't give you on its own.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My first successful campaign taught me the shape of the arc the hard way. We launched huge, hit 45% in three days, and I relaxed, thinking we had it. Then the middle hit: two weeks of near-silence, pledges trickling, the counter barely moving. I nearly panicked. But I'd saved content and energy for exactly this — so I posted updates, shared new clips, added a stretch goal, and personally re-engaged backers to share. We limped through the middle, and then the final 48 hours exploded as the deadline loomed, adding nearly as much as the launch. We finished at 130%. The lesson burned in: a campaign isn't won at launch — it's won by refusing to let the middle kill it.</p>
</div>`,
